<DOC><DOCNO> AP890320-0095 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-20-89 1229EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Maldives     03-20 0190</FIRST><SECOND>AM-BRF--Maldives,0196</SECOND><HEAD>Trial Begins for Four Maldivians Accused in Coup Attempt</HEAD><DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A trial has begun for four men whoparticipated in last year's attempt to overthrow Maldivian PresidentMaumoon Abdul Gayoom, an official in the Indian Ocean archipelagosaid Monday.   The trial of the four Maldivians began Thursday in Male, theMaldivian capital, and the defendants included Abdul Lutfi, thealleged leader of the November coup attempt, said Ibrahim HussainZaki, the Maldivian foreign secretary.   He said the trial of 45 Sri Lankans who also took part in thecoup attempt would begin soon.   Gayoom has said participants in the coup attempt could face thedeath sentence.   Sri Lankan Tamil militants led by Lutfi raided the Maldives onNov. 3, but they fled when 1,600 Indian paratroopers landed inresponse to a call for help from Gayoom.   At least 18 Maldivian civilians were killed in the raid. Most ofthe attackers were pursued by Indian naval ships, arrested andbrought to Male.   The Maldives, about 500 miles south of Sri Lanka, are made up ofabout 2,000 islands, of which only 200 are inhabited.</TEXT></DOC>